		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Happiness economics</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>Happiness economics</b> is the study of a country's <a href="/wiki/Quality_of_life" title="Quality of life">quality of life</a> by combining economists' and psychologists' techniques. It relies on more expansive notions of utility than does conventional <a href="/wiki/Economics" title="Economics">economics</a>. Although its usefulness is yet to be determined, it has become a subject of interest and often a measure of comparison with the traditional forms of measuring market health such as <a href="/wiki/GDP" title="GDP" class="mw-redirect">GDP</a> and <a href="/wiki/GNP" title="GNP" class="mw-redirect">GNP</a>. This field of studies is also called " The economy of happiness".<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
